My favorite photos from the decade (in no particular order)

Date: February 15th, 2019

There are two distinct reasons why I am so fond of the memory of taking this particular photo. The first was that, literally, the moment after I took it, the church lights turned off. This was the one and only photo I got of the church illuminated just as the sun began to rise. I hit the shutter button, looked at the photo for a quick review, and when I looked back up, the lights were off. üòÖ That‚Äôs just how it goes, I suppose.

The other reason why I enjoy the memory of this photo so much is because I was with my good friend, @lukaesenko of @photohound and @esenkoworkshops. Luka is one of the most generous and kind people that I‚Äôve met in this ‚Äútaking picture for a living‚Äù space of ours. He generously gave me a week out of his busy life to take me all around Slovenia. I highly recommend considering one of his workshops. You‚Äôd be hard pressed to find a better instructor or guide.
----------

My favorite photos from the decade (in no particular order)

Date: March 3rd, 2015

No amount of research or IG posts in your stream can ever truly prepare you for seeing the northern lights for the first time with your own eyes. I suspect every person who has had the pleasure of encountering this stupendous natural phenomenon would agree.

While my first time seeing the Aurora was actually a few days prior in Iceland, with my buds @colbybrownphotography and @jazurephotography, the lights truly gave us a show when we moved onto northern Norway... hence this photo.

I‚Äôve been quite lucky to see these lights on subsequent trips to these regions, but my first time seeing them will always hold a particular special place in my heart.
----------

My favorite photos from the decade (in no particular order)

Date: April 2, 2014

A long, long time ago, my friend, @laurenepbath, organized an influencer event around southern @australia and she was kind enough to include me as one of the participants. As you‚Äôd expect, the trip was a blast because Australia is amazing.

One early morning, I found myself roaming around Tallow Beach (thanks, jet lag) with my camera. Way off in the distance, I saw a fisherman getting his rod ready. Everything, for the most part, was perfect: crashing waves, a rocky outcrop, and a colorful, cloudy sky. The only problem was that the fisherman was about 20-30 feet to the left of where he is in this photo.

That‚Äôs when photographers begin invoking their own brand of Jedi mind control. I stood there, hundreds of feet away from this guy, and everything in me willed him to move further out towards the ocean. It was sorta supernatural, because after a few minutes, he did exactly that and positioned himself *EXACTLY* where I had hoped he would.

It‚Äôs one of those memories that will always be etched in my brain because of how beautifully the whole moment played out. So, yeah, thanks again for that wonderful trip, Lauren! ----------

My favorite photos from the decade (in no particular order)

Date: February 1st, 2013

A coworker of mine from my time at ON1 had a black and white version of this photo that he had taken hanging on his office wall. I always looked at it in amazement because of the storybook qualities the scene has.

So, you could imagine my delight when I finally had my own opportunity to visit this location. To be honest, I didn‚Äôt even try too hard to come up with a unique composition because the one I had seen in that hanging photo was, in fact, about as good as it could get.

What I did have going for me was the time of year and time of day that I took this photo. It was cool enough where a layer of fog developed in the background, providing the perfect sense of atmospheric depth. The light was also getting low, which wrapped every tree and dangling strip of lichen in a gorgeous, soft glow. Finally, there was still plenty of rushing water, which completed the overall composition.

This is another one of those photos where it feels like I took it in a different life. In some ways, that is somewhat true. But, it doesn‚Äôt prevent me from looking back at it with total fondness. This photo encapsulates why I feel that the Pacific Northwest is one of the most magical places on Earth.

My favorite photos from the decade (in no particular order)

Date: May 25th, 2010

Just about everything that could have prevented me from ever getting this photo almost did happen and should have kept me from nabbing it. The captain was refusing to let the press (of which I was part of) take one of the ship tenders to sail around the vessel. Then he refused to lower the sails. Then two of the sails broke and almost wouldn‚Äôt unsheathe. Then the seas turned into a nightmare, with ridiculous chop. Then I almost dropped my camera into the ocean when we hit a particular gnarly wave.

As it was, I constantly had one arm wrapped around a metal beam for support because of the crazy waves. At the time, I had no idea if I was going to get a single usable frame, which sort of goes with the territory for a landscape shooter battling nature. Thankfully, I was able to capture one frame that lined up quite nicely.

It was a fine way to kick off the new decade and I probably look back to this image with more fondness than nearly any other image I‚Äôve ever taken.

C: @canonusa 5D Mark II
L: Canon EF 16-35mm f/2.8L II

[Swipe for a sweet pano]
All you need is a bit of variance to fundamentally change the overall feel of a scene, even one as popular as The Watchman in @zionnps. In this case, my variable was snow. It‚Äôs not too often that you can experience a scene like this in the snow and the timing of being here for it was great, especially because it was a last minute jaunt. Hopefully, we‚Äôll see some more of the white stuff throughout the area soon. .

It was a wonderful reminder that nature and photography owe you nothing, but can reward your patience and perseverance with dividends if they choose to.

More and more, I find myself spending less time with my ultrawide lenses and far more time with my longer, telephoto glass. There‚Äôs an often fun, sometimes challenging, and always rewarding aspect to searching for the tighter details of a scene that is, in and of itself, magnificent. In this case, rather than capturing the entirety of the waterfall, I chose to isolate the base of one of its tiers. Also, I chose to do so in a horizontal composition rather than a vertical one and I think it works really well.

Yesterday, I spent the afternoon roaming around the ever-beautiful @zionnps. I was passing by the bridge near the entrance that offers a stunning view of the Watchman just after sunset and despite having photographed it many times already, I took the opportunity to do so again. I‚Äôve never been one to be bothered about whether a location, scene or landmark has been photographed a billion times by a million people. You‚Äôd laugh if you saw how many photos I have of the Brooklyn Bridge or Multnomah Falls. And, sure, the bulk of those photos may never see the light of day, but that isn‚Äôt the point.

Every day... hell, every hour, brings different variables into the mix that can result in different photos of the exact same place. Perhaps your mindset is different than before. Maybe you‚Äôre using a different lens. Perhaps it is a wild, new post-processing technique that you‚Äôll apply when you get back home. Whatever it is, there‚Äôs never a good reason to forgo taking a photo, even if it is of a popular location.
----------

Often times, obvious‚Äîor self-evident‚Äîideas that we take for granted take on a different life altogether when you hear it told, or spoken, to you. When I visited Italy‚Äôs stunning Dolomites region in February, I enjoyed a little presentation by my good bud, @seanbagshaw. As part of his talk, he discussed the importance of truly seeing the light: its qualities, where it falls, and how it interacts with shadows.

As photographers, these concepts should be pretty obvious, but it was refreshing to hear it from someone I admire nonetheless. It was like a booster shot of sorts and it helped get me in the right mindset for a week of shooting subjects that were completely defined by light.

So, my point is to not take too much of what you think you know about photography for granted. Timely reminders of practical concepts that you may already know can be as effective as learning a new topic altogether. #TheMoreYouKnow
----------
